<article>
    <h1>THE ROAD HOME (PG)</h1>
    <h2>89 min&#xAD;utes/Net&#xAD;flix</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210108/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-08"><time>2021-01-08</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | WEEKEND</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Chi­nese di­rec­tor Zhang Yi­mou had two great years in 1999 and 2000.</p>
    <p>Af­ter the re­lease of the drama Not One Less (1999) to con­sid­er­able ac­claim, he fol­lowed up with The Road Home, which won the Silver Bear (Jury Grand Prix) at the Ber­lin In­ter­na­tional Film Fes­ti­val, among oth­ers.</p>
    <p>The story, adapted by screen­writer Bao Shi from his own novel Re­mem­brance, be­gins in monochrome in the present day be­fore switch­ing to a colour-drenched mid­dle sec­tion set decades ear­lier.</p>
    <p>It de­tails the courtship between the nar­ra­tor’s mother (played by Zhang Ziyi, right fore­ground, in her film de­but) and his fa­ther (Zheng Hao), a teacher sent to her vil­lage to open a school­house. An achingly ten­der ro­mance de­vel­ops, made more fairy tale-like by the idyl­lic ru­ral set­ting.</p>
    <p>It is an ide­alised and heav­ily nos­tal­gic vi­sion of the past, filled with happy farm­ers who em­body ev­ery so­cial­ist ideal, but di­rec­tor Zhang’s crafts­man­ship makes it all work.</p>

